Tareeqk - Setup and Run Guide
Follow these steps to get the car recovery system running on your local machine.

1. Backend Setup (Laravel)
Open your terminal and go to the LARAVEL_BACKEND folder.

Install dependencies: Run composer install.

Create environment file: Copy .env.example to a new file named .env.

Generate security key: Run php artisan key:generate.

Database Configuration:

Create a MySQL database named tareeqk.

In your .env file, update DB_DATABASE, DB_USERNAME, and DB_PASSWORD.

Pusher Configuration:

Create a free account at Pusher.com.

app_id = "2121851"
key = "a634f54f94dbb9d6d523"
secret = "e39d9faccd10c606a0d6"
cluster = "ap2"

Get your App ID, Key, Secret, and Cluster.

In your .env file, set BROADCAST_DRIVER=pusher and QUEUE_CONNECTION=database.

Paste your Pusher details into the PUSHER_ fields.

Run Migrations: Run php artisan migrate.

Create Test Users:

Run php artisan tinker.

Paste the user creation code from the documentation to create a customer and a driver.

Start the Server: Run php artisan serve --host=0.0.0.0.

Start the Queue (Important): Open a new terminal in the same folder and run php artisan queue:work.

2. Web App Setup (Customer)
Open a new terminal and go to the REACT_WEB_APP folder.

Install dependencies: Run npm install.

Create environment file: Copy .env.example to .env.

Configure API:

Set REACT_APP_BACKEND_URL to http://localhost:8000.

Add your Pusher Key and Cluster.

Run the App: Run npm start. The app will open at http://localhost:3000.

3. Mobile App Setup (Driver)
Open a new terminal and go to the REACT_NATIVE_DRIVER_APP folder.

Install dependencies: Run npm install.

Find your Local IP:

Windows: Run ipconfig in CMD.

Mac: Run ifconfig in Terminal.

Look for the IPv4 Address (e.g., 192.168.1.5).

Create environment file: Copy .env.example to .env.

Configure API:

Set REACT_APP_BACKEND_URL to http://YOUR_LOCAL_IP:8000.

Add your Pusher Key and Cluster.

Start the App:

Run npm start to open the Metro Bundler.

Press a for Android or i for iOS (requires an emulator or a connected device on the same Wi-Fi).

4. How to Test
Login as Customer on the Web App (ashwin@test.com / password123).

Login as Driver on the Mobile App (driver@test.com / password123).

Create a Request on the Web App.

Check the Mobile App: The request should appear instantly without refreshing.

Accept the Request on the Mobile App and watch the Web App update automatically.

Would you like me to help you troubleshoot any specific connection issues?